### RESEARCHER-B Round 1

This research round focused on the regulatory reality that there is no separate “AI drug approval” fast lane as of mid‑March 2026: FDA’s Jan 2025 draft guidance on “Considerations for the Use of Artificial Intelligence to Support Regulatory Decision‑Making for Drug and Biological Products” lays out documentation and credibility expectations for AI in submissions (https://www.fda.gov/regulatory-information/search-fda-guidance-documents/considerations-use-artificial-intelligence-support-regulatory-decision-making-drug-and-biological?utm_source=openai), the longstanding Accelerated Approval and other expedited programs remain the legal routes for faster approvals (https://www.fda.gov/drugs/nda-and-bla-approvals/accelerated-approval-program?utm_source=openai), and the agency has already pilot‑tested AI‑assisted scientific review with plans to scale internal reviewer tools (https://www.fda.gov/news-events/press-announcements/fda-announces-completion-first-ai-assisted-scientific-review-pilot-and-aggressive-agency-wide-ai?utm_source=openai); practical implication: AI can compress discovery and improve submission quality/efficiency, but it does not eliminate the need for clinical evidence or regulatory standards, so next steps are to convert this into a watchlist, quantify valuations, and map near‑term catalysts for a Sept 2026 horizon. Vibe check: (green) = real progress.

